loning, expression and protein purification. The gene encoding full-length Ngl3p (systematic name, yml118) was amplified from S. cerevisiae genomic DNA using primers Ngl3LICtev1-20 (5β€²-GACGACGACAAGATGGAGAATCTTTATTTTCAGGGCATGGA TAGCCAAGTAGAAGG-3β€²) and Ngl3LIC1494-1518 (5β€²-GAGGAGAAGCCCGGTTTATTTTAAGCTATGCACTTTCTC-3β€²) and inserted into pET30Ek/LIC (Novagen) by the ligation-independent cloning (LIC) method (LIC sites are underlined). The fusion protein contains an N-terminal 6Γ— His tag and a Tobacco Mosaic Virus (Tev) protease site (bold). The active site Ngl3p mutant (Ngl3pH485A) was constructed by site-directed mutagenesis of pET30 Ek/LIC-Ngl3wt using primers 5β€²-GAGAATATGCTAGTGATGCCATTTCCCTAATG-3β€² and 5β€²-CATTAGGGAAATGGCATCACTAGCATATTCTC-3β€², for which the site of mutation is underlined.Protein expression was carried out in E. coli BL21 (DE3) Rosetta cells grown at 37Β°C in 2Γ—TY with 50β€‰ΞΌg/ml kanamycin and 34β€‰ΞΌg/ml chloramphenicol until a OD600 of 0.6β€“0.8, cooled on ice for 30β€‰min, then induced with 0.5β€‰mM isopropyl Ξ²-d-1-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG) and incubated at 20Β°C overnight. After harvesting, the cells were resuspended in buffer A (50β€‰mM Trisβ€“HCl, pH 8.0, 300β€‰mM KCl, 5β€‰mM MgCl2, 5β€‰mM Ξ²-mercaptoethanol (BME), 20β€‰mM imidazole, 10% glycerol and Complete Protease Inhibitor Cocktail tablets (Roche) and lysed by high-pressure homogenization at 15β€‰000β€‰psi. The crude extract was ultra-centrifuged at 50β€‰000β€‰r.p.m. at 4Β°C before loading on a 5β€‰ml His-trap chelating nickel-column (Qiagen) pre-equilibrated in buffer A. The column was then washed with buffer B (50β€‰mM Trisβ€“HCl, pH 8.0, 1β€‰M KCl, 5β€‰mM MgCl2 and 5β€‰mM BME) and eluted using 500β€‰mM imidazole in buffer A. The eluate was dialysed overnight at 4Β°C into buffer A in the presence of His-tagged Tev protease at a ratio of 1:200 (w/w) Tev to Ngl3p. The sample was then reapplied to the Ni-column to remove the Tev protease, uncleaved Ngl3, and any proteins non-specifically binding the column. The run-through was concentrated to about 8β€‰mg/ml and loaded on a 24β€‰ml Superdex 200 10/300 GL column (GE healthcare) pre-equilibrated in buffer C (10β€‰mM Hepes, pH 7, 100β€‰mM KCl, and 5β€‰mM BME) at 4Β°C. Finally, the protein was concentrated to 20β€‰ΒµM using VivaSpin spin filters (10.000 MWCO PES, VivaScience) at 4Β°C and stored at β�’80Β°C in 50% glycerol. Protein concentration was measured using the Nanodrop ND-1000 spectrophotometer and an extinction coefficient of 1.18 OD280/mg (ExPaSy ProtParam). Rrp6p12β€“536 was purified essentially as described previously (30).In vitro degradation assaysRNA substrates were synthesized with either a 5β€²-carboxyflourescein (FAM) or 5β€²-carboxytetramethylrhodamine (TAMRA) label (RNA-polyC10), except RNA-endoA10, which had both 5β€²-FAM and 3β€²-TAMRA labels (DNA Technology, Invitrogen, Microsynth and Dharmacon), gel purified and dissolved in water to 100β€‰nM. The RNA oligo used for creating the circular RNA had the sequence, 5β€²-CAGCUCCGCAUTCCCUUUCCCAAAAAAAAAA-3β€², where UT denotes a modified uracil base to which a TAMRA fluorophore is attached (Microsynth). Circular RNA was produced by incubating the labelled, 5β€²-phosphorylated, linear RNA with T4 RNA ligase 1 (New England Biolabs) and 1β€‰mM ATP in the supplied buffer for 15β€‰min at 37Β°C. The circular form was then isolated by gel purification on a 18% denaturing acrylamide gel, eluted into 10β€‰mM Mes, pH 6.5, precipitated and dissolved in water to 140β€‰nM. In vitro reactions with Ngl3p contained at least 50 times molar excess of enzyme (0.5β€‰ΒµM) over substrate (1β€“10β€‰nM) and reactions at standard conditions were carried out at 30Β°C in reaction buffer containing 10β€‰mM Mes, pH 5.5, 10β€‰mM KCl, 5β€‰mM MgCl2 and 1β€‰mM DTT. Reactions with Rrp6p contained only 5β€‰nM protein and were carried out in 10β€‰mM Tris, pH 8.0, 50β€‰mM KCl, 1β€‰mM MgCl2 and 2β€‰mM BME at 30Β°C. After incubation, reactions were quenched by addition of an equal volume of RNA loading buffer (8β€‰M Urea, 50β€‰mM Trisβ€“HCl, pH 7.5, and trace bromophenol blue) and the resulting RNA fragments separated by denaturing gel electrophoresis in 20β€‰cm 18β€“20% denaturing polyacrylamide gels (8β€‰M urea in 1Γ— TBE) running β�Ό3β€“4β€‰h at 9β€‰W in 1Γ—TBE at room temperature. RNA ladders were made by limited alkaline hydrolysis of the individual RNA substrates in 50β€‰mM NaHCO3/Na2CO3 at pH 8.9 for 14β€‰min at 96Β°C. A Typhoon Trio Imager (GE healthcare) was used to visualize the gels and data quantification was done using TotalLab Quant.Microscale thermophoresisEquilibrium binding experiments were carried out at a constant low, fluorescent RNA concentration of 10β€‰nM, while titrating in protein in 16 steps from 0.14β€‰nM to 4.6β€‰ΞΌM. The protein titration series was prepared by serial dilution of a 9.22β€‰ΞΌM Ngl3p stock solution in protein storage buffer (5β€‰mM Hepes, pH 7, 50β€‰mM KCl, 2.5β€‰mM BME and 50% glycerol) and 1:1 mixing of protein and RNA in binding buffer (30β€‰mM Mes, pH 5.5, 10β€‰mM KCl, 1β€‰mM DTT and 0.05% Tween-20). Experiments were carried out using Ngl3wt in the absence of divalent metal ions, where it remains inactive. The raw fluorescent thermophoresis signal was recorded in triplicate from a Monolith NT.115 microscale thermophoresis system (NanoTemper) and normalized by scaling to 0β€“100%. Fitting was done using a sigmoidal dose-response model with variable slope and the EC50 value of the curve used as a measure for the KD.Yeast growth assayYeast strains were constructed by back-crossing of the ccr4Ξ”::KAN and ngl3Ξ”::KAN strains from BY background (Open Biosystems) with a BY trp1Ξ” strain. Double deletion mutants were obtained from crossing of the ccr4Ξ”::KAN and ngl3Ξ”::KAN single deletions and individual deletions were confirmed by gene-specific PCR. For yeast growth assays, BY trp1Ξ” derivatives were diluted to A600β€‰=β€‰0.2, spotted in 10-fold dilutions onto YPAD plates, and incubated at 18Β°C for 5 days and 30 or 37Β°C for 2 days.
