. cerevisiae gl3p is an active 3β€²β€“5β€² exoribonuclease in vitro. For the biochemical analysis of S. cerevisiae Ngl3p, the full-length enzyme was expressed in E. coli as a His-tagged fusion protein cleavable by Tev protease. The fusion protein (63.3β€‰kDa) was purified by tandem Ni-NTA chromatography separated by Tev cleavage, and subsequent gel filtration yielded highly pure protein in three steps (Supplementary Figure S1A). The cleaved and purified wild type enzyme, denoted Ngl3pwt, elutes corresponding to a molecular weight of 60β€‰kDa during gel filtration, very near the theoretical molecular weight of 58β€‰kDa, suggesting that Ngl3p is a globular, monomeric protein in solution (Supplementary Figure S1B). Gel filtration also served to change the enzyme into a minimal buffer allowing later addition of specific divalent metal ions during the functional analysis.To analyse the enzymatic activity of Ngl3p in vitro, we carried out a series of RNA degradation experiments in which the enzyme was incubated with defined, chemically synthesized and 5β€² fluorescently labelled RNA and DNA substrates. Following incubation, samples were separated by denaturing polyacrylamide gelelectrophoresis and the resulting 5β€² fragments visualized with a resolution down to one nucleotide by scanning fluorometry. As deadenylases are relatively slow enzymes, their activity is best studied under pre-steady state conditions, where the protein is in molar excess over RNA (31). Consequently, due to the risk of cross-contamination with other nucleases co-purified from the expression host, inclusion of an active site mutant is critical in such experiments to ensure that the correct activity is being studied. We therefore constructed an H485A active site mutant, Ngl3pH485A, in which an essential histidine in the EEP active site motif was changed into alanine (Supplementary Figure S2, marked with a red asterisk). The mutant was purified essentially as the wild type enzyme.First, Ngl3wt was incubated with a 30β€‰nt RNA oligo consisting of 20β€‰nt of generic sequence with little or no secondary structure followed by 10 adenosine residues mimicking a poly-adenylated mRNA (RNA-polyA10, Figure 1A). During initial assays carried out at standard conditions at pH 7β€“8 with 100β€‰mM KCl and 5β€‰mM Mg2+, the enzyme showed only trace activity, and a more thorough screening for the reaction optimum was therefore carried out at pH values ranging from 3.5 to 9, salt concentrations from 5 to 1000β€‰mM, and temperatures from 10β€“50Β°C all in the presence of 5β€‰mM Mg2+ (Figure 1B and Supplementary Figure S3). In these experiments, the rate of degradation was quantified as the relative amount of partly or fully degraded RNA relative to full length RNA (30β€‰nt) by integration of the gel bands. Optimal activity was observed at 30Β°C, low ionic strength (5β€“10β€‰mM KCl), and a relatively low pH value of 5.5β€“6.5 with very little activity below pH 5.5 and above 7. All subsequent reactions were carried out in 10β€‰mM KCl at pH 5.5 and 30Β°C at which conditions the enzyme displayed robust activity.
Figure 1.Ngl3p is a 3β€²β€“5β€² exonuclease active at low pH. (A) Fluorescently labelled, mRNA-like substrates with either 10 or 21 adenosine residues at the 3β€²-end, where (F) represents the 5β€²-carboxyfluorescein label. (B) pH optimum of Ngl3p shown as the percentage of degraded RNA at different pH values. The pH optimum is pH 6.2 (dashed line). (C) Metal ion requirements. Gel showing degradation of RNA-polyA10 in the presence of 5β€‰mM Mg2+, 5β€‰mM Mn2+, 1β€‰mM Zn2+ and combinations of these. In lane 9, the reaction contained 7.1β€‰mM Mg2+, 75β€‰ΒµM Mn2+ and 220β€‰ΒµM Zn2+(33), and in lane 10, 25β€‰mM EDTA was added. The transiently stabilized fragment (21β€‰nt) is indicated. (D) Degradation of RNA-polyA10 by Ngl3pwt over time. L is an RNA ladder made by partial alkaline hydrolysis. The RNA ladder sizes (30β€“20β€‰nt) and the stabilized fragment (21β€‰nt) are indicated and for the lane β€�H485Aβ€™, RNA-polyA10 was incubated with the active site mutant, Ngl3pH485A. (E) Degradation of RNA-polyA21. The points of pausing at 10 and 8β€‰nt are indicated.EEP-type nucleases are dependent upon one or more divalent cations for binding RNA, activating water for hydrolysis and stabilizing the negatively charged transition state during the cleavage reaction (32). To investigate the metal ion requirements of Ngl3p, we studied degradation of RNA-polyA10 in the presence of combinations of milimolar quantities of Mg2+, Mn2+ and/or Zn2+ (Figure 1C). Incubation of 10β€‰nM RNA for 1β€‰h at 30Β°C in the reaction buffer including either 5β€‰mM Mg2+ (lane 1) or 50 times molar excess of Ngl3wt (lane 2) but not both, resulted in little or no RNA degradation illustrating that the enzyme is inactive in the absence of divalent metal ions. Including either 5β€‰mM Mg2+ (lane 3) or 5β€‰mM Mn2+ (lane 4), on the other hand, resulted in degradation of the substrate as visible by the shortening of the 5β€²-labelled RNA substrate, while a much slower rate of reaction was observed in the presence of Zn2+ (lane 5), similar to what was observed for the cellular deadenylase, Pop2p (31). Mixing two of the ions showed intermediate reaction rates, compatible with Zn2+ having a dominant negative effect on activity (lanes 6β€“8). Interestingly, a mix of all three ions mimicking as closely as possible their intracellular concentrations [7.1β€‰mM Mg2+, 75β€‰ΞΌM Mn2+, 220β€‰ΞΌM Zn2+, (33)] resulted in an activity whereby a fully deadenylated species of β�Ό20β€‰nt was temporarily stabilized (lane 9). Finally, as expected, inclusion of EDTA abolished any trace activity in the purified enzyme (lane 10). We conclude that Ngl3p is a divalent metal ion-dependent nuclease that most likely binds Mg2+ in vivo due to its higher cellular concentration.Ngl3p transiently stabilizes a fully deadenylated RNA speciesTo analyse the mechanism by which Ngl3p degrades the poly A-containing RNA, we studied the reaction over time at lower RNA concentration (1β€‰nM) and in the presence of 5β€‰mM Mg2 (Figure 1D). Under these conditions, we observe progressive shortening of the substrate indicating exonucleolytic degradation in the 3β€²β€“5β€² direction. Degradation continues until all substrates have reached a length of exactly 21β€‰nt (0β€“30β€‰min) after which the enzyme continues into non-poly A RNA (30β€“180β€‰min). Ultimately, after overnight incubation, Ngl3p would degrade the substrate completely (data not shown). The RNA species transiently stabilized in this manner corresponds to the 20β€‰nt of generic sequence and the first of the 10 adenosine residues in the 3β€²-end, which shows that poly-A discrimination by Ngl3p is not confined to the ultimate 3β€² base, but probably involves recognition of several 3β€² adenosine residues. The active site mutant Ngl3pH485A showed no degradation of the substrate even after 60β€‰min incubation (lane β€�H485Aβ€™). To test whether the observed pausing at the beginning of the poly-A tail is indeed due to the sequence of the 3β€²-end and not the result of complex RNA structure, we repeated the experiment with a substrate of identical length but with 21 adenosine residues at the 3β€²-end (RNA-polyA21, Figure 1A and E). Consistently, the wild type enzyme degraded this substrate down to about 10β€‰nt length compatible with removal of all but the last adenosine. Afterβ€‰30β€‰min, degradation has continued into non-poly A sequence and appears to stop at the first G encountered (8β€‰nt). We conclude that Ngl3p is active as a 3β€²β€“5β€² riboexonuclease and tends to pause at the end of poly-A stretches, reminiscent of what has been observed for other known cellular deadenylases, such as Schizosaccharomyces pombe Pop2p (16,17).Ngl3p does not degrade RNA secondary structureNext, we asked if the poly-A tract has to be located at the very 3β€²-end to promote degradation by Ngl3p. To analyse this, we used a similar substrate in which the poly-A tract was β€�internalβ€™ to the sequence, i.e. surrounded on both 5β€² and 3β€² sides by non-poly A sequence (Figure 2A). The 3β€² extension to the poly-A stretch was pyrimidine-rich and ended with a single A. In this case, the enzyme does not recognize the poly-A tract and degrades the last seven nucleotides slowly with a complicated degradation pattern (Figure 2B). This shows that the poly-A tract has to be present in the very 3β€²-end to be recognized correctly by the enzyme. We then asked if Ngl3p could degrade an RNA containing a strong secondary structure element followed by a poly-A sequence (Figure 2A and C). Interestingly, the poly-A tail following the strong secondary structure element is not degraded as fast as the completely single-stranded RNA. This might indicate that the structured RNA interferes with degradation, perhaps restricting entry of the 3β€²-end into the active site. Degradation eventually halts after removal of eight residues (lengthβ€‰=β€‰22β€‰nt) and the enzyme is not able to proceed through the RNA secondary structure (Figure 2C). Finally, as many members of the EEP family are also active on DNA, we tested if Ngl3p would be able to degrade a deoxy nucleotide substrate with a sequence identical to RNA-polyA10 (Figure 2D). In this case, DNA is degraded in a 3β€²β€“5β€² exonucleolytic fashion similar to RNA, but the reaction is much slower than for poly-A RNA, suggesting that this may not be the natural substrate. We conclude that although Ngl3p is able to degrade both DNA and single-stranded regions of structured RNAs as well as non-poly A RNA, optimal activity is achieved with fully single-stranded RNA bearing a poly-A sequence at the very 3β€²-end.
Figure 2.Ngl3p requires a 3β€² poly-A tail and does not degrade dsRNA. (A) Oligos used in this figure, where (F) represents the 5β€²-carboxyfluorescein (FAM) label. (B) Degradation of RNA-intA10, a substrate with an internal oligo-A tract. The sequence of the oligo is shown along the side. (C) Degradation of an RNA containing a strong secondary structure element followed by a 10β€‰nt poly-A tail (RNA-stemloopA10). The shortest product is 22β€‰nt, corresponding to the stem structure plus two overhanging 3β€² residues. (D) Degradation of a deoxynucleotide substrate having the same sequence as RNA-polyA10.Ngl3p is inactive on poly-G RNAGiven the observed poly-A specificity, we asked if Ngl3p would be able to initiate degradation of other monotonous 3β€² sequences, poly-uridine, poly-cytidine and poly-guanosine. Four oligos containing the 20β€‰nt generic sequence followed by 10 identical residues (A, U, C or G) were incubated at 10β€‰nM with Ngl3p in parallel reactions, and aliquots removed at different time points. As shown in Figure 3A, Ngl3wt is able to degrade both poly-pyrimidine sequences (RNA-polyC10 and RNA-polyU10) reasonably efficiently and at similar rates, although much slower than the corresponding poly-adenosine sequence. Additionally, the pausing at the end of the monotonous sequence region is not observed. In contrast, the poly-G substrate was left essentially untouched illustrating that Ngl3p cannot initiate degradation of this type of 3β€² sequence. A plot of the total amount of NMP produced over time as function of the type of 3β€² sequence allows direct comparison of the observed differences in activity (Figure 3B). This reveals approximately constant rates of reaction for the poly-C and poly-U substrates of 3.78β€‰Γ—β€‰10β�’5β€‰sβ�’1 and 2.20β€‰Γ—β€‰10β�’5β€‰sβ�’1, while poly-A is degraded about 10 times faster at 2.64β€‰Γ—β€‰10β�’4β€‰sβ�’1 until reaching a plateau approaching 100β€‰nM NMP corresponding to an average removal of 10 adenosines from each substrate molecule.
Figure 3.Ngl3p prefers poly-A RNA. (A) Parallel time-course degradation experiments with 10β€‰nM RNA-polyA10, RNA-polyU10, RNA-polyC10 and RNA-poly-G10. The constant diffuse bands seen for RNA-polyC10 around 12, 15 and 20β€‰nt arise from absorption of the bromophenol blue dye at the TAMRA excitation wavelength. (B) Quantification of the degradation experiments in A converted to nanomolar NMP produced at each time point. Error bars represent the standard error of the mean (SEM) of three independent experiments. Errors are relatively large at longer time points due to weakening of the fluorescent label. (C) Measured affinities towards RNA and DNA substrates with different 3β€² end sequences. The KD values measured are 226β€‰Β±β€‰63β€‰nM (RNA-polyA10), 195β€‰nMβ€‰Β±β€‰95 (RNA-polyU10), 96β€‰Β±β€‰22β€‰nM (RNA-polyG10) and 161β€‰Β±β€‰37β€‰nM (DNA-polyA10). The error bars represent 95% confidence intervals.The inability of Ngl3p to degrade poly-G RNA could in theory arise either from lack of binding these RNAs (i.e. low affinity) or an intrinsic lack of activity on such substrates. In order to resolve this ambiguity, we measured the affinity of Ngl3pwt towards RNA-polyA10, RNA-polyG10, and RNA-polyU10 as well as DNA-polyA10 by microscale thermophoresis (MST), a novel technique that measures changes in fluorescent mobility upon heating the sample with an infrared laser (34). Since binding of protein to the fluorescently labelled RNA significantly alters mobility in solution, a signal can be recorded when titrating a fixed, low amount of RNA (10β€‰nM) with increasing protein concentrations at otherwise identical conditions. Binding affinities measured as the dissociation constant, KD, can then be calculated by fitting the normalized MST fluorescence using a dose-response type sigmoidal model (Supplementary Figure S4). The RNA affinities were measured using the wild type enzyme in the absence of Mg2+ to avoid degradation of the substrates during the experiment. Using this approach, we measured dissociation constants of β�Ό200β€‰nM for RNA-polyA10 and RNA-polyU10, around 100β€‰nM RNA-polyG10 and about 150β€‰nM for DNA-polyA10 (Figure 3C). The measured affinities are all in the 100β€“200β€‰nM range and thus within the same order of magnitude. Remarkably, however, the affinity towards RNA-polyG10 is significantly higher than those for the other substrates. As the conditions used for the biochemical experiments (10β€‰nM RNA and 500β€‰nM protein) are well above all binding constants we can thus conclude that the inability of Ngl3p to degrade RNA-polyG10 and the slower reaction rate on DNA-polyA10 are not due to lower affinity, on the contrary as RNA-polyG10 was bound strongest, rather that the enzyme is inherently less active on these substrates.Ngl3p approaches the 3β€²-end in a different way than DEDD nucleasesAs several members of the EEP family are known endonucleases, we wanted to investigate whether Ngl3p, in addition to functioning as a 3β€²β€“5β€² exonuclease, could also cleave RNA by endonucleolysis. To test this, we constructed an RNA substrate containing two different fluorophores, a 5β€²-fluoresceine and a 3β€²-TAMRA attached to the 3β€²OH group (RNA-endoA10) with the rationale that the presence of a bulky 3β€² fluorophore should inhibit 3β€²β€“5β€² exonuclease activity prior to any endonucleolytic cleavage event. Moreover, this substrate allows tracking the fate of both 5β€²- and 3β€²-ends after cleavage by scanning the gels separately for each fluorophore. Apart from this modification, the substrate is identical to RNA-polyA10. To test the assumption that 3β€²β€“5β€² exonucleases cannot generally degrade this 3β€²-blocked RNA, we first incubated RNA-endoA10 with the catalytic fragment of the S. cerevisiae nuclear exosome component, Rrp6p (residues 12β€“536), which is of the DEDD type and shows robust 3β€²β€“5β€² exonuclease activity in vitro (30). In contrast to RNA-polyA10, which is quickly degraded by Rrp6p (Figure 4A, lane marked β€�polyAβ€™), no degradation is visible for RNA-endoA10 (Figure 4A), showing that DEDD-type exonucleases cannot initiate degradation due to the presence of the 3β€² fluorophore. In contrast, incubation of RNA-endoA10 with Ngl3p shows a progressive degradation pattern similar to RNA-polyA10 ending at the end of the poly-A tract. However, as the initial cleavage in this case could have occurred either by endo- or exo-nucleolysis, we repeated the experiment using a circular RNA, in which a TAMRA group had been attached to an internal uracil base prior to circularizing the substrate with RNA Ligase 1 (Figure 4B). We observed no degradation of the circular substrate, thus suggesting that Ngl3p cannot cleave RNA in a classical, endonucleolytic fashion. However, since it is still able to cleave the 3β€² blocked substrate, this indicates that it uses a different, and more open, way to approach the 3β€²-end than DEDD-type nucleases. In summary, our data provide evidence that Ngl3p primarily functions as an exonuclease, but unlike other 3β€²β€“5β€² exonucleases is able to degrade substrates with a blocked 3β€²-end. Future structural investigations will reveal the molecular basis for this subtle difference.
Figure 4.Ngl3p degrades a 3β€² blocked but not a circular RNA substrate. (A) Degradation of RNA-endoA10 by Ngl3pwt and Rrp6p12-536 (5β€²-end fragments). The lane marked β€�polyAβ€™ is Rrp6p12β€“536 incubated with RNA-polyA10. (B) Incubation of Ngl3pwt with a circular RNA substrate labelled internally with a TAMRA label. The lane marked β€�linear RNAβ€™ is the phosphorylated RNA oligo prior to circularization.Deletion of Ngl3p does not affect growth of a ccr4Ξ” strainSince the poly-A specificity of Ngl3p suggests an involvement of the enzyme in cellular deadenylation, we finally investigated if deletion of ngl3 in S. cerevisiae affected the growth phenotype in a ccr4Ξ” background, which is already deadenylation compromized (Figure 5). ccr4Ξ” exhibits a strong cold- and mild temperature-sensitive growth phenotype, while deletion of the gene coding for Ngl3p does not have any measureable effect on the growth of the yeast cells consistent with its non-essential role. In comparison, double mutant, ccr4Ξ”ngl3Ξ”, shows a growth phenotype very similar to ccr4Ξ”, showing that the deadenylation-compromized cells are not further challenged by the concomitant deletion of Ngl3p. This suggests that Ngl3p is not part of the main Ccr4-NOT mediated deadenylation pathway or another RNA degradation pathway involving the majority of cellular RNAs, but is more likely required for processing of specific poly-adenylated substrates.
Figure 5.Deletion of ngl3 does not affect the growth of a ccr4Ξ” yeast strain. Growth phenotypes of the S. cerevisiae wt, ccr4Ξ”, ngl3Ξ” and ccr4Ξ”/ngl3Ξ” double deletion mutants. Ten-fold serial dilutions of cells were spotted onto agar plates and grown at the indicated temperatures.
